article.headline: O'Neal can't stomach Northwest
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- There's an argument to be made for calling Jermaine O'Neal the best player in the Eastern Conference. Imagine what he could do at full strength. O'Neal spent the day fighting off a stomach illness and a migraine headache, then scored 30 points in the Indiana Pacers' 101-94 win over the Seattle SuperSonics on Friday night. "I was up at 7 o'clock calling the team doctor," O'Neal said. "For the most part, I slept all afternoon, then I got a little meal in. I just wanted to give what I could give. It was enough to get a win." Al Harrington, starting in place of the injured Ron Artest, had 18 points and 14 rebounds. The Pacers trailed 45-44 at halftime but broke the game open in the third quarter by outscoring Seattle 36-15. "We're deep," Harrington said. "We're a team to be reckoned with. Of our four losses, two have been right at the end. We've been challenging people. We hold guys below their averages. We're just doing a good job on the defensive end." The Sonics had their fans standing with an exciting rally in the fourth quarter, but they couldn't quite offset their poor defense in the third quarter. Ronald Murray scored 18 of his 20 points in the second half and Rashard Lewis scored 12. But the Sonics are a team that relies on its shooting accuracy, and one look at their shots told it all: Lewis was 3-for-11, Murray was 6-for-16, Vladimir Radmanovic shot 2-for-10 and Luke Ridnour went 2-for-9. "We scored only three or four (points) in seven minutes," Radmanovic said. "That's terrible. You can't win a game like that. We've got to make more shots." Artest sat out for the second time in four games because of back spasms. Jeff Foster, who had 10 offensive rebounds in Indiana's 101-78 win over Seattle last month in Indianapolis, had eight this time and finished with 14 rebounds. The Pacers, who tied the Lakers with a league-high 16 victories, held a 43-37 advantage on the boards. "Most of the time they're going in to double-team Jermaine," Foster said. "He has a knack for turning away. Most of the time, somebody has to fill on the other side, and most of the time it's one of their smaller guys. I'm able to push him a little." Reggie Miller scored 14 points for the Pacers and Kenny Anderson had 12 against the team with whom he spent much of last season. After O'Neal committed a turnover on Indiana's first possession of the second half, the Pacers scored on 16 of the next 17 trips. Harrington completed a three-point play with 3:46 on the clock for a 68-49 lead, capping a 20-2 run. "They played the best third quarter we've played all year," Pacers coach Rick Carlisle said. "That was the key to the game." Indiana got baskets from Kenny Anderson, O'Neal and a 3-pointer by Miller to close the third quarter with a 7-1 burst that made it 80-60 going into the fourth, and it turned out to be just enough as Seattle charged back. Sonics coach Nate McMillan went with a smaller lineup, and Murray scored eight points during a 20-10 burst that pulled Seattle to 90-80 with 5:41 remaining. "We fought," Ridnour said. "Unfortunately, it wasn't enough. We've just got to play the whole game like that." Lewis added a 3-pointer to pull the Sonics to 92-85 with 2:39 to play, and Richie Frahm had two more 3-pointers in the final minute to make it 99-93. But the Pacers kept Seattle from getting too close by going 11-of-12 from the foul line in the fourth quarter. "You can't dig a hole that deep and expect to get out of it," McMillan said. Indiana came in with the best record in the Eastern Conference (15-4), with two of those losses coming in the first three games of its current five-game road trip. They improved to 9-2 on the road this season.

Game notes
Sonics G Ray Allen will being workouts Monday, his first practices since ankle surgery Nov. 1. The team announced no date for his return. ... McMillan was whistled for a technical foul for arguing after Lewis received an offensive foul after a collision with Miller. ... Murray sported a new look: a headband with his head shaved.
